$VER: Toxic Boards Guide 2.00 (7.9.96)

@node "Introducing" "Introducing"

   This Tool is just another CNet BBS PFile (also known as "Door") for the
   CNet Bulletin Board System Version 3.0 or higher. It shows you the
   expansion of your powerfull BBS so that every user can see what you have
   inside your AMIGA (tm) computer.
@endnode
@node "Legal Stuff" "Legal Stuff"

   This AREXX Script (incl. the executable) is FREEWARE! Please do not change
   the code or remove the credits.

   Toxic Boards copyright by Sascha 'Enigma' Reissner 1996 the Sysop of the
   "TOXIC WASTE BBS".

   Toxic Boards used identify.library with permission by Richard Koerber.
@endnode
@node "What does it do" "What does it do"

   The AREXX Script executes my tool called boards.exe that uses the
   expansion.library to get some information about your expansion boards.
   These information are now processed by the identify.library which currently
   knows 200+ boards (v3.1) then everything is printed out in a nice looking
   way. Just Do it!
@endnode
@node "How to install" "How to install"

   For AutoInstall just use the included Installer script (lets hope that
   you have the original INSTALLER in your C: dir.

   For manual installation just copy the whole dir to the location of your
   choice and include Board in your PFiles and/or BBSMenu section.
   
   eh.. easy.. isn't it?
@endnode
@node "Settings" "Settings"
 
   Well nothing to setup here..  
@endnode
@node "Future Plans" "Future Plans"

   Well I`ll release all of the tools used in my BBS. Hope someone is
   interested.

   Other tools released by me.

   - SRS!_CNetStartupManager : Like the WBStartup Drawer.. throw some
                               ANSIs, TEXTs, ASCIIs in it and they will
                               be displayed after the login.
   - SRS!_wHO                : Another WHO replacement (suits perfectly
                               to GC_MENUS (RIP extension).
   - SRS!_CDiNFO             : Tells the user what CD is online and shows
                               a nice ANSI and a description
   - TBoards107              : Older Version of this tool



   Well what should I improve ?!?.. Think it makes what it should do.
@endnode
